ss_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aForms of Exile in Jewish Literature and Thought deals with the concept of exile on many levels-from the literal to the metaphorical. It combines analyses of predominantly Jewish authors of Central Europe of the twentieth century who are not usually connected, including Kafka, Kraus, Levi, Lustig, Wiesel, and Frankl. It follows the typical routes that exiled writers took, from East to West and later often as far as America. The concept and forms of exile are analyzed from many different points of view and great importance is devoted especially to the forms of inner exile. In Forms of Exile in Jewish Literature and Thought, Bronislava Volková, an exile herself and thus intimately familiar with the topic through her own experience, develops a unique typology of exile that will enrich the field of intellectual and literary history of twentieth-century Europe and America.  afunded by Knowledge Unlatched  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAlienation (Philosophy) in literature. 0aCentral European literaturexJewish authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aCentral European literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aExile (Punishment) in literature. 0aExiles in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Jewish.2bisacsh  aAlma Mahler.  aArnost Lustig.  aArthur Schnitzler.  aBruno Schulz.  aCentral Europe.  aEgon Hostovsky.  aElie Wiesel.  aExpulsion.  aFranz Kafka.  aFranz Werfel.  aHermann Broch.  aHermann Ungar.  aHolocaust.  aHugo von Hofmannsthal.  aJewish history.  aJiri Weil.  aJoseph Roth.  aJudaism.  aKarl Kraus.  aLadislav Fuks.  aMarcel Proust.  